fields.name: Rabai Mpya (Krapf Memorial)
fields.description: Est. 1846. The cradle of Christianity in Kenya.

fields.name: Vasco da Gama Pillar (Malindi)
fields.description: Built 1498. Earliest European Christian symbol on the coast.

fields.name: The Portuguese Chapel (Malindi)
fields.description: c. 1502. Oldest Christian place of worship in East Africa.

fields.name: Frere Town (Kisauni)
fields.description: Est. 1875 by CMS for freed slaves.

fields.name: Holy Ghost Cathedral (Mombasa)
fields.description: A historic Roman Catholic cathedral in Mombasa, representing the return of the Catholic mission to the island in the late 19th century.

fields.name: Jomvu Mission
fields.description: An early Methodist mission station established near Mombasa creek. It played a vital role in the initial evangelism of the Mijikenda tribes.

fields.name: Sagalla (St. Mark's Church)
fields.description: Located inland in Taita Taveta, this tin-roofed church was built in the 1890s and served as a critical stopover for missionaries traveling from the coast to the interior.

fields.name: Mazeras Mission
fields.description: Key Methodist gateway to the Duruma communities.

fields.name: Holy Ghost Cathedral
fields.description: Historic Roman Catholic cathedral in Mombasa.

fields.name: Fort Jesus Chapel Ruins
fields.description: Ruins of the Portuguese chapel inside the fort.

fields.name: St. Luke's Makupa
fields.description: One of the oldest CMS churches serving railway workers.

fields.name: Jomvu Methodist Mission
fields.description: Early Methodist station established by Thomas Wakefield.

fields.name: Gede Ruins (Mosque/Church debate)
fields.description: While predominantly Islamic, artifacts suggest trade links with Christian empires.

fields.name: St. Thomas Church (Kilifi)
fields.description: Historic Anglican church serving Kilifi creek.

fields.name: Takaungu Slave Port
fields.description: Major slave exit point; later focus for abolitionists.

fields.name: Kaloleni Giriama Mission
fields.description: St. John's Church center for evangelism.

fields.name: Lamu Portuguese Fort
fields.description: Site of struggle between Omani and Portuguese.

fields.name: Takwa Ruins
fields.description: Holy site visited by interfaith scholars.

fields.name: Kaya Kauma (Sacred Forest)
fields.description: Traditional sacred site, later a point of dialogue with missionaries.

fields.name: Gede Ruins
fields.description: Ancient ruins suggesting trade links with Christian empires.

fields.ethiopian_text: And behold! He cometh with ten thousands of His holy ones...
And it came to pass when the children of men had multiplied...
And all the others together with them took unto themselves wives... and they began to go in unto them and to defile themselves with them.
fields.analysis: Describes the corruption of humanity by the Watchers.

fields.ethiopian_text: Bind Azazel hand and foot...
And the angel of the presence spake to Moses...
And after the completion of the seven years...
I was small among my brethren...
My hands made a harp, and my fingers fitted a psaltery.

But ungodly men with their works and words called it to them: for when they thought to have it their friend, they consumed to nought, and made a covenant with it, because they are worthy to take part with it.
fields.analysis: A philosophical reflection on death and ungodliness.

fields.ethiopian_text: Nevertheless through envy of the devil came death into the world: and they that do hold of his side do find it.
fields.analysis: This text explicitly links the Serpent of Genesis to the Devil/Satan, a connection not explicitly made in the Hebrew Genesis.

fields.ethiopian_text: But the souls of the righteous are in the hand of God, and there shall no torment touch them.
fields.analysis: A key verse often used in liturgies regarding the afterlife.

fields.ethiopian_text: All wisdom cometh from the Lord...
My son, if thou come to serve the Lord...
A faithful friend is a strong defence...
Commend not a man for his beauty...
In three things I was beautified...
Honour a physician with the honour due unto him...
I am Raphael, one of the seven holy angels...
Do that to no man which thou hatest...
Praise God, for he hath not taken away his mercy...
Afterward did he shew himself upon earth...
O Lord, Almighty God of our fathers, Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob, and of their righteous seed...
fields.analysis: A penitential prayer included in the Ethiopian liturgy, emphasizing God's mercy.

fields.ethiopian_text: Whatsoever is brought upon thee take cheerfully, and be patient when thou art changed to a low estate.
For gold is tried in the fire, and acceptable men in the furnace of adversity.
For she [Wisdom] is the brightness of the everlasting light, the unspotted mirror of the power of God, and the image of his goodness.
fields.analysis: High Christology often applies this description of Wisdom to Christ.

fields.ethiopian_text: Give alms of thy substance; and when thou givest alms, let not thine eye be envious, neither turn thy face from any poor, and the face of God shall not be turned away from thee.
Be ye zealous for the law...
Seven brethren with their mother...
The beginning of pride is when one departeth from God, and his heart is turned away from his Maker.
Pride was not made for men, nor furious anger for them that are born of a woman.
Wisdom found no place where she might dwell...
Wisdom went forth to make her dwelling among the children of men, and found no dwelling-place: Wisdom returned to her place, and took her seat among the angels.
fields.analysis: Explains the lack of wisdom in the world.

fields.ethiopian_text: And against the angels whom He had sent upon the earth, He was exceedingly wroth, and He gave commandment to root them out of all their dominion...
fields.analysis: Further details on the judgment of the Watchers.

fields.ethiopian_text: And who shall tell it to my Lord? The Lord himself, the Lord heareth.
He sent his angel and took me from my father's sheep, and anointed me with the anointing oil.
fields.analysis: Confirmation of David's anointing by Samuel.

fields.ethiopian_text: Now the Babylonians had an idol, called Bel, and there were spent upon him every day twelve great measures of fine flour, and forty sheep, and six vessels of wine.
fields.analysis: An addition to the book of Daniel in the Ethiopian canon exposing idolatry.

fields.ethiopian_text: And they walked in the midst of the fire, praising God, and blessing the Lord.
fields.analysis: The prayer of Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego inside the furnace.

fields.ethiopian_text: And he took a wife, whose name was Susanna...
And then Michael, Uriel, Raphael, and Gabriel looked down from heaven and saw much blood being shed upon the earth...
fields.analysis: Lists the four archangels acting as intercessors.

fields.ethiopian_text: He that loveth his son causeth him oft to feel the rod, that he may have joy of him in the end.
And there I saw One who had a head of days...
fields.analysis: Vision of the Son of Man.

fields.ethiopian_text: And he was six jubilees of years...
And it happened, after that Alexander son of Philip...
It is therefore a holy and wholesome thought to pray for the dead...
Love righteousness, ye that be judges...
Nevertheless through envy of the devil came death...
But the souls of the righteous are in the hand of God...
For she is the brightness of the everlasting light...
O Lord, Almighty God of our fathers...
Now the Babylonians had an idol...
